1. Overview

Calgary is a city locates in southern Alberta, Canada, and it is the third most populous municipality in Canada. As of 2021, its population reached 1,306,784, and its land area is about 820.63 square kilometers. The city is vulnerable to floods since it has extensive development along the Elbow River and Bow River. Moreover, the risk of flooding will continue to increase as climate change ongoing; the accelerated snowmelt in spring will add extraordinary pressure on the watercourse and city sewer system. As one of the largest cities in the country, Calgary has a relatively comprehensive flood monitoring approach and has collected a fair amount of data for floods. By using the given flood satellite image and the DEM, along with the landcover data our group collected, we fitted a generalized linear model to predict flood in Calgary. With the given flood inundation data, we were able to cross-validate the model we established and then applied it to Edmonton, a comparable city to Calgary, to predict inundation for the city.

2. Data Preparation and Visualization

Inundation is highly related to factors such as land cover, slope, blue spot that identify flood sensitive areas, and distance to water. In this analysis, we collected the DEM, city boundary, and landcover data for both Calgary and the comparable city Edmonton then generated 500*500m fishnet for both cities. Based on these datasets, we calculated the average distance to stream, percent Inundation, percent developed area, percent water coverage, average slope within each fishnet by using ArcGIS Pro. And here is a visualization of these variables for Calgary. When preparing the data, we assumed that the cell floods (Inundation_indicator == 1) when the percent of inundation (area) is greater than or equal to 25%.

3. Modeling

3.1 Split Dataset

To test the validation of the model, this analysis split the fishnet dataset for Calgary into 70/30 training-test sets.

set.seed (47)

train <- Calgary_dat_new[sample, ]
test  <- Calgary_dat_new[-sample, ]

As the plot below shows, most of the cells labeled as not inundate tend to have a very low probability of flood based on our model, and areas labeled as “inundate” tend to have a more diversified probability of inundation based on the established model.

3.3.2 Confusion Metrics and ROC

To calculate the confusion metrics, we assumed that the cell will be considered as Inundated when the predicted inundation rate is greater than or equal to 0.25, in accordance with our assumption of identifying inundate cells in the beginning of this analysis.As the result show, when the threshold were set at 0.25, the accuracy of the model is around 0.9512, and the Area Under the Curve (ROC) is about 0.8805.

Inundation_testProbs$predClass  = ifelse(Inundation_testProbs$pred >= .25 ,1,0)

3.3.3 Cross Validation

To test the power of the established model trained on the training dataset, we applied cross-validation to the entire dataset, and the cross-validation will automatically generate the test dataset. As the result below shows, the average accuracy of the 100 folds is about 0.9494193.

Inundation_ctrl <- trainControl(method = "cv", 
                     number = 100, 
                     savePredictions = TRUE)

Inundation_cvFit <- train(as.factor(Inundation_indicator) ~ .,  data = Calgary_dat_new %>% 
                                                as.data.frame() %>%
                                                select(-geometry,-Dis_Stream,-Pct_Inun, -Shape_Area,-Shape_Leng, -BS_YN),

3.3.5 Map Confusion Matrix

Here is a map showing the confusion matrix result spatially. As the map below shows, cells in green indicate areas that are predicted to be flooded and are inundation areas in reality. Cells in blue are areas predicted to be non-inundation areas and are also not inundated in reality; Cells in red are areas that are inundated areas but are predicted as non-inundation areas by the model. Such inaccuracy may induce safety risks when planning for flooding. And finally, the cells in orange indicate areas that are not inundated but are predicted as inundation areas. This type of inaccuracy may lead to extra expenditure when doing environmental planning. However, no model is perfect, and there are many approaches to improve the model, such as adjusting our assumption on what ratio is considered inundation.

Calgary_dat_new %>%
  mutate(cmResult=case_when(allPredictions < 25 & Inundation_indicator==0 ~ "True_Negative",
                              allPredictions >= 25 & Inundation_indicator==1 ~ "True_Positive",
                              allPredictions < 25 & Inundation_indicator==1 ~ "False_Negative",
                              allPredictions >= 25 & Inundation_indicator==0 ~ "False_Positive")) %>%
  ggplot()+
  geom_sf(aes(fill = cmResult), color = "transparent")+
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("red3","Orange","Light Blue","darkseagreen4"),
                    name="Outcomes")+
  labs(title="Confusion Metrix") +
  mapTheme

5. Scenario

In the previous analysis, we categorized a cell as Inundate when the percent of inundation area exceeds or is equal to 25% of the total cell area. The confusion matrix result indicated some predictions turned out to be False Negative. To predict the worst scenario, we set this inundation threshold to > 0, which means if the cell has greater than 0% of land deemed as inundation in the satellite image, the entire cell will be considered inundated.

5.1 Define New Calgary Data

Calgary_dat_new2 <- Calgary_dat %>%
  mutate(Inundation_indicator = as.integer(ifelse(Pct_Inun >0 ,1, 0)),  # change percent of inundation to a dummy indicator.
         Dis_Stream_mile = Dis_Stream/1609.34)  # convert from meter to mile for better histogram visualization.

5.2 Visualize New Data

ggplot() + 
  geom_sf(data=Calgary_dat_new2, aes(fill=as.factor(Inundation_indicator)), color = "transparent") +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("olivedrab4", "deepskyblue2"),
                    labels = c("Not Inundated","Inundated"),
                    name = "") +
  geom_sf(data=Calgary_dat_new %>% 
               filter(Inundation_indicator == 1), 
               fill="cadetblue1",colour=NA) +
  mapTheme +
  labs(title="Inundation Area Using 25% vs. 0% Threshold",
      subtitle="lighter blue color indicating cells identified as inundation when using 25% area
threshold, darker blue cells are identified as inundation when using 0%")

5.3 Build Model

set.seed (47)
sample <- sample.int(n = nrow(Calgary_dat_new2), size = floor(.7*nrow(Calgary_dat_new)), replace = F)
train2 <- Calgary_dat_new2[sample, ]
test2  <- Calgary_dat_new2[-sample, ]

As a result of InundationModel2 shows, the -Pct_BS became an insignificant predictor, we tested the BS_YN, a dummy indicator showing whether the cell has any blue spot. The result of InundationModel3 turned out showing the BS_YN dummy is a significant predictor. Speaking of the Pct_Built, it turned out to be insignificant for models 2 and 3. When we removed it in model 4, the coefficient for other predictors did not change much, and the AIC slightly improved from 1740.3 to 1719.3, therefore, removing the Pct_Built could be a better option.

5.4 Model Validation

As the result below shows, when we use the 0% area threshold to identify inundation cells, the accuracy returned from confusion matrix is 0.8555, which is lower than the model we built when using the 25% area threshold. The ROC is 0.8848, which is a slighter higher than that for the model built in step 3. Such discrepancy might result from the imbalanced distribution of the class of the dataset. As the grouped result of the new dataset show, when the area threshold is set to 0%, there are 2966 cells identified as 0 - not inundate, and 587 classified as 1 - inundate, which is slightly more balanced than the previous dataset. The accuracy returned from cross-validation is 0.8737787, which is also lower than that for the previous dataset and model.

5.6 Map Confusion Matrix
